# AZ-104 Lab: Azure Virtual Networks and VNet Peering

## Project Overview

This lab demonstrates how to create and manage Azure networking resources in Microsoft Azure. The project covers Virtual Networks (VNets), Subnets, Network Security Groups (NSGs), Virtual Machines, and VNet Peering to enable secure communication between isolated Azure networks.

---

## Architecture

```text
Resource Group
     →
VNet-App (10.10.0.0/16)
     →
Subnet-App (10.10.1.0/24)
     →
VM-App-01

Resource Group
     →
VNet-DB (10.20.0.0/16)
     →
Subnet-DB (10.20.1.0/24)
     →
VM-DB-01

VNet Peering
     ↔
Private Communication
```

---

## Step 1: Create a Resource Group

A Resource Group was created to organize all resources used in this lab.

### Screenshot

![Resource Group](screenshots/01-resource-group.png)

### Key Learning

* Resource organization
* Logical grouping of Azure resources
* Simplified resource management
* Easier cleanup of Azure resources

---

## Step 2: Create the Application Virtual Network

A Virtual Network was created to host application resources and virtual machines.

### Configuration

| Setting       | Value        |
| ------------- | ------------ |
| VNet Name     | vnet-app     |
| Address Space | 10.10.0.0/16 |
| Subnet Name   | subnet-app   |
| Subnet Range  | 10.10.1.0/24 |

### Screenshot

![VNet App](screenshots/02-vnet-app.png)

### Key Learning

* Azure Virtual Network deployment
* Address space planning
* Network segmentation using subnets

---

## Step 3: Create the Database Virtual Network

A second Virtual Network was created to simulate a backend or database environment.

### Configuration

| Setting       | Value        |
| ------------- | ------------ |
| VNet Name     | vnet-db      |
| Address Space | 10.20.0.0/16 |
| Subnet Name   | subnet-db    |
| Subnet Range  | 10.20.1.0/24 |

### Screenshot

![VNet DB](screenshots/03-vnet-db.png)

### Key Learning

* Network isolation
* Multi-tier network design
* Azure network architecture

---

## Step 4: Create Network Security Groups

Network Security Groups were created to control inbound and outbound traffic.

### NSGs Created

| NSG     |
| ------- |
| nsg-app |
| nsg-db  |

### Screenshot

![Network Security Groups](screenshots/04-network-security-groups.png)

### Key Learning

* Traffic filtering
* Network security
* Access control policies

---

## Step 5: Associate NSGs with Subnets

The Network Security Groups were associated with their respective subnets.

### Associations

| NSG     | Subnet     |
| ------- | ---------- |
| nsg-app | subnet-app |
| nsg-db  | subnet-db  |

### Screenshot

![NSG Association](screenshots/05-nsg-subnet-association.png)

### Key Learning

* Subnet-level security
* Traffic management
* Azure network protection

